{"summary":{"verdict":"BLOCK","one_liner":"Race condition on shared mutable counters — parallel promises mutate `results.processed`, `results.failed`, and `results.errors` concurrently, producing incorrect counts and potential data loss under real load."},"critical_findings":[{"title":"Race condition on `results.processed++` and `results.failed++` across concurrent promises","risk":"The `++` operator is not atomic. It reads the current value, increments, and writes back. When multiple promises resolve in the same microtask batch (common with I/O-bound work), two callbacks can read the same value before either writes, losing increments. With 500 deliveries, final counts will be silently wrong — `processed + failed < deliveryIds.length`.","severity":"Critical","location":"processBatchDeliveries, lines with `results.processed++` and `results.failed++`","reproduction":"Run with 500 deliveries where `processDelivery` resolves near-simultaneously (e.g., cached/fast responses). Compare `results.processed + results.failed` against `deliveryIds.length`. They will diverge. Easiest repro: mock `processDelivery` to resolve immediately (`Promise.resolve()`), run 500 items, repeat 100 times — count mismatches will appear.","fix":"Collect per-item outcomes into an array via `Promise.all` (which preserves ordering and is safe), then derive counts:

```typescript
const outcomes = await Promise.all(
  deliveryIds.map(async (id) => {
    try {
      await processDelivery(id);
      return { id, success: true } as const;
    } catch (err) {
      return { id, success: false, error: (err as Error).message } as const;
    }
  })
);
const processed = outcomes.filter(o => o.success).length;
const errors = outcomes.filter(o => !o.success).map(o => ({ id: o.id, error: o.error }));
return { processed, failed: errors.length, errors };
```","time_to_fix":"15 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Batch result counts must equal total input count (processed + failed === deliveryIds.length)"},{"title":"Unbounded concurrency — 500 parallel requests with no throttling","risk":"Launching 500 simultaneous `processDelivery` calls will overwhelm downstream services (database connection pools, HTTP endpoints, rate limits). This causes cascading timeouts, socket exhaustion, or 429/503 errors, turning a batch of mostly-good deliveries into a batch of mostly-failed ones.","severity":"High","location":"processBatchDeliveries, `Promise.all(deliveryIds.map(...))`","reproduction":"Call with 500 IDs against a service with a connection pool of 20 or an API rate limit. Observe mass failures from pool exhaustion or throttling.","fix":"Use a concurrency limiter (e.g., `p-limit`, `Promise.allSettled` with chunking, or a semaphore):

```typescript
import pLimit from 'p-limit';
const limit = pLimit(20); // tune to downstream capacity
await Promise.all(deliveryIds.map(id => limit(() => processDelivery(id))));
```","time_to_fix":"20 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Batch processing must not overwhelm downstream services"},{"title":"Untyped error access — `err.message` throws on non-Error rejections","risk":"If `processDelivery` throws a string, number, or undefined (common with third-party libs or re-thrown fetch errors), `err.message` is `undefined` and the error detail is silently lost. In strict TS with `useUnknownInCatchVariables`, this won't even compile.","severity":"High","location":"catch block: `err.message`","reproduction":"Have `processDelivery` call `throw 'connection timeout'` (a string). The logged error will be `undefined` instead of the actual message.","fix":"Type the catch variable and normalize:
```typescript
catch (err: unknown) {
  const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);
  // use message
}
```","time_to_fix":"5 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Error reporting must capture actual error details for debugging"}],"important_issues":[{"title":"No partial-failure observability","description":"If 250 of 500 deliveries fail, the caller gets a summary object but there is no logging, no metrics emission, and no alerting hook. In production, a 50% failure rate should trigger an alarm, not just return a number.","location":"processBatchDeliveries return value"},{"title":"Promise.all fails-fast behavior is masked but still risky","description":"While the try/catch inside the map prevents Promise.all from short-circuiting, if the map callback itself throws synchronously before the try (e.g., a null id causing a crash in the closure setup), Promise.all rejects and all in-flight work is abandoned with no result returned.","location":"Promise.all wrapping"}],"suggestions":["Add an input guard: if `deliveryIds` is empty, return early with zero counts instead of invoking `Promise.all` on an empty array (harmless but wasteful).","Consider `Promise.allSettled` instead of `Promise.all` with internal try/catch — it's the idiomatic pattern for this use case and eliminates the shared-state temptation.","Add a total count to BatchResult (`total: deliveryIds.length`) so callers can assert `processed + failed === total` as an invariant check."],"production_readiness":{"deployment_risks":"Silent data corruption: batch counts will be wrong under real concurrency, leading to incorrect downstream decisions (e.g., reporting all deliveries processed when some were lost). 500 parallel calls will strain connection pools.","rollback_capability":"N/A — inline function, rollback is a code revert.","backward_compatibility":"Fix does not change the BatchResult shape, so it is backward-compatible.","monitoring_coverage":"None — no logging or metrics on failure rates within a batch.","breaking_changes":{"api_breaking":false,"db_destructive":false,"shared_library":false,"auth_security":false,"data_pipeline":true,"config_changes":false,"details":["Incorrect batch counts flow into data pipelines that depend on accurate processed/failed tallies"]},"safe_to_deploy":false,"rollback_plan":"Revert to previous implementation or fix the race condition before deploying."},"escalations":[],"confidence":{"level":95,"high_confidence_areas":["Race condition on shared counters is deterministic and well-understood","Unbounded concurrency is a known production anti-pattern","Untyped catch variable is verifiable from the code"],"low_confidence_areas":["Exact failure rate depends on downstream service latency profile — faster responses make the race more likely"],"assumptions":["processDelivery performs async I/O (network/DB) — if it were purely synchronous the race window narrows but the pattern is still incorrect","TypeScript strict mode settings are unknown — err.message may or may not compile depending on tsconfig"]}}
